<paragraph id="8B8A36FAE62EFFA800B7F8061478FDB4" blockId="0.[151,1084,2020,2045]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1437,152,611]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="130" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">
<typeStatus id="548E8858E62EFFA900B7F8061582F82A" box="[151,201,2021,2045]" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D79E62EFFA90106F8071737F82A" authority="Becker, 1912" authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1912" box="[294,636,2020,2045]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Hippelates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mellinus">
<emphasis id="B941EAE8E62EFFA90106F80714BBF82B" box="[294,496,2020,2044]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Hippelates mellinus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B0BE62EFFA901D6F8071737F82A" author="Becker, T." box="[502,636,2020,2045]" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" pagination="21 - 256" refId="ref6660" refString="Becker, T. (1912) Chloropidae. Eine monographische Studie. IV. Teil. Nearktische Region. V. Neotropische Region. Nachtrag. I. Palaearktische Region, II. Aethiopische Region. Annales historico-naturales Musei nationalis hungarici, 10, 21 - 256." type="journal article" year="1912">Becker, 1912</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(subsequent designation, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B0BE62EFFA903A3F807117BF82A" author="Duda, O." box="[899,1072,2020,2045]" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" pagination="159 - 172" refId="ref6853" refString="Duda, O. (1931) Die neotropischen Chloropiden (Dipt.). 1. Fortsetzung: Nachtrag, Erganzungen, Berichtigungen und Index. Folia Zoologica et Hydrobiologica, 3, 159 - 172." type="journal article" year="1931">Duda, 1931: 165</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B941EAE8E62FFFA800B7FF7B1459FF64" bold="true" box="[151,274,152,179]" pageId="1" pageNumber="130">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body color background yellow, pruinose; ocellar triangle covered with fine short dark microtrichiae and with a large black spot anteriorly, occupying about ¾ of the frons length; facial carina sharp, generally complete; eye pale, with dense short pale hairs; ocellar setae short and reclinate; postocellars long and cruciate; interfrontal setulae curved inwards; about eight short fronto-orbital setae; outer vertical seta strongly developed, as long as postocellars; inner vertical seta circa three quarters length of outer vertical seta; frons pollinose, covered with short dense pilosity; gena with more than two rows of pilosity, unordered; vibrissa distinct; postpedicel entirely yellow, as long as deep; fore coxa with a row of strong setae anteriorly; tibial spur present or absent; 1+2 notopleurals; a row of long prescutellar setae; acrostichal setulae absent; scutum with dorsal markings usually orangish, almost indistinct; katepisternum pilose dorsally; male femoral organ composed by 3–4 rows of small warts (
<figureCitation id="130E2A7FE62FFFA80520FE5A1005FE04" box="[1280,1358,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1929]" captionTargetBox="[226,1353,194,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[214,1373,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–14. Chaethippus carioca sp.nov. paratypes. 7, habitus (scale bar 1 mm). 8, head in dorsal view. 9, head and thorax in profile (arrow indicates the fore coxa strong setae). 10, detail of the head in dorsal view. 11, tibial organ. 12, femoral organ. 13–14, male terminalia in terminal view (scale bar 0.1 mm). Abbreviations: bas, basiphallus; cer, cercus; dis, distiphallus; ep, epandrium; fr, frons; oc tr, ocellar triangle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904960/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="130">fig. 12</figureCitation>
); tibial organ oval (
<figureCitation id="130E2A7FE62FFFA80100FE3E1426FE20" box="[288,365,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1929]" captionTargetBox="[226,1353,194,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[214,1373,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–14. Chaethippus carioca sp.nov. paratypes. 7, habitus (scale bar 1 mm). 8, head in dorsal view. 9, head and thorax in profile (arrow indicates the fore coxa strong setae). 10, detail of the head in dorsal view. 11, tibial organ. 12, femoral organ. 13–14, male terminalia in terminal view (scale bar 0.1 mm). Abbreviations: bas, basiphallus; cer, cercus; dis, distiphallus; ep, epandrium; fr, frons; oc tr, ocellar triangle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904960/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="130">fig. 11</figureCitation>
); wing hyaline, as in 
<figureCitation id="130E2A7FE62FFFA80247FE3E178AFE20" box="[615,705,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1900,1925]" captionTargetBox="[227,1359,187,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[215,1371,179,1872]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Chaethippus mellinus. 1, habitus (scale bar 1 mm). 2, head in frontal view (arrow points to the strong seta on the fore coxa). 3, wing. 4, head and thorax in dorsal view. 5, epandrium in terminal view. 6, male terminalia in ventral view (scale bar 0.1 mm). Abbreviations: bas, basiphallus; cer, cercus; dis, distiphallus; ep, epandrium; gon, gonites; hyp, hypandrium; phal, phallapodeme; phal s, phallapodemic sclerite; st 6, remnant of the 6th sternite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904958" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904958/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="130">figure 3</figureCitation>
, cell dm-m large, anal lobe developed; abdomen yellow, almost inconspicuous brownish bands dorsally; remnant of the sixth abdominal sternite present, with a pair of small setae; hypandrium poorly sclerotized; distiphallus striate (
<figureCitation id="130E2A7FE62FFFA802C0FDC61666FDE8" box="[736,813,549,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1904,1929]" captionTargetBox="[226,1353,194,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[214,1373,181,1878]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–14. Chaethippus carioca sp.nov. paratypes. 7, habitus (scale bar 1 mm). 8, head in dorsal view. 9, head and thorax in profile (arrow indicates the fore coxa strong setae). 10, detail of the head in dorsal view. 11, tibial organ. 12, femoral organ. 13–14, male terminalia in terminal view (scale bar 0.1 mm). Abbreviations: bas, basiphallus; cer, cercus; dis, distiphallus; ep, epandrium; fr, frons; oc tr, ocellar triangle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904960" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904960/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="130">fig. 13</figureCitation>
); female terminalia telescopic, with cercus narrow and long (
<figureCitation id="130E2A7FE62FFFA800F8FDAA146DFDB4" box="[216,294,585,611]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–24" captionStartId="8.[151,262,1915,1940]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,465,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[154,1433,453,1890]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 20–24. Chaethippus maculatus sp.nov. holotype. 20, habitus (scale bar 1 mm). 21, head in dorsal view. 22, abdome ventral (scale bar 0.1 mm). 23, female terminalia, dorsal. 24, female terminalia, ventral. Abbreviations: cer, cercus; epi, epiproct; hypo, hypoproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904964" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904964/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="130">fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
